  "response": "During Bill Clinton's presidency, allegations of infidelity surfaced, most notably with Gennifer Flowers and Monica Lewinsky.\n\n*   **Gennifer Flowers:** Flowers alleged a long-term affair with Clinton. While Clinton initially denied the affair, he later admitted to a single encounter during a deposition in the Paula Jones case.\n*   **Monica Lewinsky:** The affair with Lewinsky, a White House intern, led to impeachment proceedings against Clinton. He initially denied the affair, but later admitted to an \"inappropriate relationship.\"\n\nHillary Clinton's response to these allegations has been complex and varied over time. Publicly, she initially defended her husband, dismissing the accusations as politically motivated attacks. She famously appeared on 60 Minutes with him after the Flowers allegations, portraying a united front. During the Lewinsky scandal, she accused a \"vast right-wing conspiracy\" of targeting her husband.\n\nPrivately, sources close to the Clintons have suggested that she was deeply hurt and angry by the affairs. Some reports indicate that she considered divorce during the Lewinsky scandal, but ultimately decided to stay in the marriage.\n\nOver the years, Hillary Clinton has rarely spoken directly about the affairs in detail, focusing instead on her public life and political career. In her autobiography \"Living History,\" she addressed the Lewinsky scandal, describing it as a painful and difficult time for her and her family.",
